    "created_at": "2016-04-20T22:42:08Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-04-20T22:42:56Z",
    "body": "> Personally, I always considered running third party content in Electron to be potentially dangerous. I think if anyone wants to run third party content, be a browser, etc they should fork Chromium and build off that. \n\nI think this would exclude Electron from being useful to a lot of apps. Doesn't slack technically run third-party content via soundcloud/etc. embeds? Even if the third-party content is in an iframe, it still can exploit chrome memory vulns and such.\n\nIn addition, if you load first-party remote content over HTTP, it's basically the same as running arbitrary third-party content.\n\nIt might well be true that Brave's security model is more strict than Electron can feasibly accomodate (in which case we do the work of tracking updates more closely in our fork). But it's up to the Electron maintainers to make their security goals clear to Electron users.\n"
  },
