    "created_at": "2016-04-20T23:30:35Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-04-20T23:30:35Z",
    "body": "Electron is based on a base of multiple millions lines of code. Those are a broad range of attack vectors. \n\n@paulcbetts  It's wrong to think you are safe as long as you don't display HTML/JS from Internet. Consider an Electron app opening PDF, media or even picture file from another person, oops, and Chromium had multiple known high vulnerabilities in PDFium (the pdf handling library), media, etc. Let's just pick some of them:\n\nHigh CVE-2016-1649: Buffer overflow in libANGLE. \nHigh CVE-2016-1645: Out-of-bounds write in PDFium. \nHigh CVE-2015-8126: Out-of-bounds access in libpng.\n\nIssues like this will continue to happen in the future. It's only a matter of time before someone sends a picture to Slack channel and BOOM, if you continue to think like this.\n\nDo not make excuses why you don't rebase. I don't think there is even any security goal here, or the team has seriously reviewed this.\n"
  },
