    "created_at": "2016-04-21T05:11:23Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-04-21T05:11:23Z",
    "body": "@baconface From what I can see Electron is marketed as a framework for creating desktop apps. I'm not sure why Node integration is of high concern to you for the main process only. \n\n> There isn't much more warning needed than understanding your app is going to be in a browser with a Node.js context.\n\nSure if by app you mean remote web content. That isn't our case though.\n\n> I am not trying to come off as troll. But....\n\nNeeding to prefix with this means something troll like is probably coming. \nI'll note quickly that you're making claims about bad decisions, and about the Electron project being \"meant\" to have bad security.\n\n> I feel like I am on crazy pills trying to stress using a project meant to break sandboxing/security to perform it's job is likely not a good platform where sandboxing/security should be considered priority.\n\nI don't think Electron stated they never want the ability to sandbox or be secure with regards to remote content.  \n\nIt comes down to, out of the box Electron is not today ideal for full remote content serving securely.  Which is more fine for some apps than others.  Our fork fixes those problems and we're upstreaming as long as it's accepted.  \n\nWe're also spending resources to help get Chromium upgrades in faster and prepared earlier.  Many of the tasks that get in Electron are done by the needs of the apps using it, as they need it.  Excluding browsers would be a disservice to other Electron apps that casually access and display remote content.\n"
  },
